1. Generate random arrays of size n
2. Make 3 copies of the same array
3. Sort copy 1 using Heap sort
   Sort copy 2 using Merge sort
   Sort copy 3 using Quick sort
4. Check if all sorted arrays are the same
5. Measure time taken by each Algorithm
6. Repeat this 10 times
7. Calculate average, minimum and maximum time
8. Estimate constant c using:
   T(n) ≈ c × n log₂ n

Code Flow of Execution:
1. Import libraries
2. Define heapify()
3. Define heap_sort()
4. Define merge_sort()
5. Define merge()
6. Define quick_sort()
7. Define measure_sorting_time()
8. Set n = 100 and trials = 10
9. Create empty time lists
10. Start trial loop
11. Generate random array
12. Make 3 copies
13. Run heap sort and measure time
14. Run merge sort and measure time
15. Run quick sort and measure time
16. Compare sorted outputs
17. Store times
18. Repeat steps 11–17 ten times
19. Define calculate_statistics()
20. Calculate statistics for all algorithms
21. Print final comparison table

All three algorithms have O(nlogn) expected or standard
complexity, but their constant factors differ in practical
implementation. 
In my experiment, Quick Sort showed the smallest estimated
constant and it was the fastest.
For different inputs, machine conditions, or pivot choices,
results can change.